  "footnotes": [
    "Khorezm (Chorasmia): the oasis civilization around the lower Amu Darya delta; one of the oldest irrigated agricultural societies in Central Asia; the Afrigid dynasty maintained local autonomy for centuries; the Anushteginid Khwarazmian Empire rose from here to briefly dominate Persia and Central Asia before the Mongol catastrophe of 1221",
    "Transoxiana (Sogdiana / Mawarannahr): the fertile interfluvial land between the Amu Darya and Syr Darya rivers, meaning 'what is beyond the river' in Arabic; the Sogdians were the master merchants of the Silk Road from the 2nd century BCE to the 8th century CE; under the Samanids (819–999), Bukhara became a center of Islamic learning; Timur made Samarkand the imperial capital",
    "Fergana: the enclosed high-altitude valley at the eastern end of modern Uzbekistan; renowned in Han Chinese sources for its 'heavenly horses' (tianma) which prompted the Han–Dayuan War (104–101 BCE); the Tang Anxi Protectorate administered it until the Battle of Talas (751); the Khanate of Kokand (1709–1876) was the last indigenous Central Asian state",
    "Battle of Talas (751 CE): the decisive clash between Abbasid forces and the Tang Dynasty near Taraz; the Arab-led victory halted Chinese expansion westward and opened Transoxiana to full Islamization; captured Chinese prisoners are credited with transmitting papermaking technology to the Islamic world",
    "Samanid dynasty (819–999): the first great Persian-language renaissance dynasty; Bukhara under the Samanids produced Ibn Sina (Avicenna), the geographer al-Biruni, and the poet Rudaki; their patronage established New Persian as a literary language",
    "Timurid Empire (1370–1507): Timur (Tamerlane), born near Samarkand, built an empire from Anatolia to India; his grandson Ulugh Beg constructed an observatory in Samarkand that produced the most accurate star catalogue before the telescope; the dynasty's collapse gave way to the Shaybanid Uzbek confederation",
    "Soviet national delimitation (1924): Stalin's reorganization of Central Asia drew borders dividing Uzbek and Tajik speakers; historically Persian/Tajik cities (Samarkand, Bukhara) were assigned to the Uzbek SSR while significant Uzbek populations remained in what became the Tajik SSR"
  ]
}
